\section*{Materials and Methods}

\subsection*{Sample collection}

\textit{F. rufa}, nest material (pine needles and resin) and soil within 1m radius of a nest were collected in September 2020 from Harlestone Firs, a forested area of predominantly fir trees (Harlestone Road, New Duston, Northampton, UK; GPS coordinates: 52.267750, -0.955719). Samples were collected by depositing ants, nest material and soil separately into clean zip-loc plastic bags, sealed and stored at -20$^{\circ}$C until further use. 

\subsection*{Isolation and sequencing of bacteria}
Preparation of samples for isolation took place using aseptic technique. Samples were placed into 1ml Eppendorph tubes and crushed using a pestle into 10$\mu$L or 100$\mu$L PBS and vortexed for 30s, and the liquid was transferred onto agar plates. A variety of media were used including nutrient agar, Trypticase Soy Agar (TSA), MRS and modified AE medium (8g/L yeast extract, 15g/L peptone, 10g/L D-glucose, 5mL/L ethanol (99.8\%), 3mL/L acetic acid, final pH 3.5). Plates were supplemented with 0.1g/L cycloheximide to inhibit growth of fungi, and incubated for 7 days at\SI{30}{\celsius} either in aerobic conditions or in semi-anaerobic Candlewick jars. Colonies with distinct morphologies were re-streaked onto fresh agar plates and colony PCR performed. Single colonies were picked with a sterile pipette tip which was used as template by dipping into 50 $\mu$ L 1x PCR master mix (DreamTaq Green PCR Master Mix; ThermoFisher) with primers 27F (5'-AGAGTTTGATCCTGGCTCAG-3') and 530R (5'-CCGCNGCNGCTGGCAC-3') or 1492R (5'-GGTTACCTTGTTACGACTT-3'). The primer pair 27F-530R amplify a ~500bp region of the 16S rRNA gene spanning hypervariable regions V1 to V3, whereas 27F-1492R amplify a ~1500bp region spanning the entire 16S rRNA gene from V1 to V9. PCR conditions were as follows: 1 cycle of \SI{95}{\celsius} for 15 min; 35 cycles of: \SI{95}{\celsius} for 30s, \SI{55}{\celsius}, \SI{72}{\celsius} for 2 minutes; 1 cycle of \SI{72}{\celsius} for 5 minutes; pause at \SI{4}{\celsius}. 5ÂµL from each PCR reaction was run on a 1\% agarose gel at 80V for 60 mins to determine whether a band was present at ~500bp. Where a single band of ~500bp was obtained and where the corresponding no-template control did not produce any bands, PCR reactions were purified using the [insert kit] kit. Purified DNA was quantified using Qbit HS DNA Assay kit and sent for Sanger Sequencing with GATC. Single colonies from re-streaked plates were inoculated into liquid media and grown to an OD of 0.8-1.2, from which glycerol stocks were made for long-term storage, with a final concentration of 30\% glycerol. To extract genomic DNA, glycerol stocks were used to create fresh streak-plates from which colonies were picked and used to inoculate 12.5 mL liquid media in a 50 mL falcon tube and grown at \SI{30}{\celsius} for 24h. Genomic DNA was extracted using the Qiagen Blood and Tissue Kit, with the enzymatic lysis pre-treatment step included. DNA was quantified using Qbit HS DNA Assay and stored at -\SI{20}\celsius. Purified genomic DNA was sent to MiGS (Pittsburgh, USA) for whole genome sequencing. 

\subsection*{Predicting prophages in genomes}
Whole genome sequences of bacteria were input into PHASTER \citep{arndt_phaster:_2016} to predict prophages. 

\subsection*{Optimising bacterial growth}
To determine required growth conditions, growth curves were produced for each isolate by inoculating an overnight culture into a 96 well micro-plate containing sterile media. Growth was monitored using a Varioskan machine, by measuring changes in OD every 30 minutes over 48h. 

From \citep{rubin_dietary_2019}:
The PMAnalyzer pipeline was used to analyze the growth curves. The PMAnalyzer pipeline receives OD files from the microtiter plate reader as an input and uses the SciPy Python numerical library to model each growth curve. Each growth curve was fitted with the Zwietering model to predict the y0 (OD600 nm where growth begins), lag time, maximum growth rate, and biomass yield. 
Differences between growth curves were analyzed by comparing experimental wells to controls using a method similar to one developed by Firsov who determined that the antimicrobial effect of any compound could be measured by directly comparing the growth of cells when the compound is present or absent. Some compounds were excluded from the heatmap analysis because they formed precipitates in the wells or were too opaque to accurately measure OD600 nm. Although these compounds could not be used for growth curve analyses, they were suitable for flow cytometry.

