\subsection*{Effect of bacteria on ant survival - Planned work}
Methods from \citet{chapuisat_wood_2007}.
We recorded the survival of adult workers or larvae when exposed to each bacterium, compared with a bacteria-free control. Single workers were kept in 5.5 cm diameter Petri dishes with a filter paper at the bottom. The ants were provided with ad libitum 8\% sugar water. Each control and treatment group had 20 replicates. 0.5 ml of peptone solution containing each bacterium at a concentration of \num{4e9} CFU ml\si{^-^1} was deposited in the centre of the filter paper, close to but not on the ant. The challenge-free controls received 0.5 ml of peptone solution. The entire filter paper became damp, so that the individuals probably came into direct contact with the micro-organisms, as infection is likely to occur through oral or cuticular contact.

The impact of potential pathogens on the survival of larvae was tested by placing three larvae in small artificial nests made of 9 cm circular plastic boxes with a filter paper covering the bottom of the nest and a central layer of plaster connected to a small underneath water reservoir (Passera et al. 1988). The nest was covered with a dark plastic flowerpot and placed in a 19Ã14 cm foraging arena lined with fluon to prevent escape. We provided sugar water and a protein-rich jelly made of honey, eggs and agar. Fifteen workers fed and tended the larvae. The design of these experiments was similar to that of the single adult workers, except the concentrations of micro-organisms (10\si{^1^1} CFUml\si{^-^1}), which was adapted to the larger box size and higher number of individuals. All experiments took place at \SI{25}{\celsius}. We recorded the survival of single adult workers and larvae on a daily basis, over 20 and 11 days, respectively, and removed corpses to prevent contamination. 

